An Evaluation on Students' Earnings after obtaining a Bachelor's Degree:

By: Shifa Bhutta

Introduction:

The main purpose of this is to take you through the data sceince pipeline. As a college student myself, I have often wondered about student earnings and what effects them. Is it specific to a region and if the most expensive colleges are really worth it and lead to significantly higher paying jobs than colleges that do not cost as much. I will be using the US Department of Education's database. This dataset is only applicable to students in America so that is the only country I will be looking at. Also, varying levels of degress (Bachelor's, Associate's,Masters,Doctorate) effects your earnings significantly. This tutorial will only focus on undergrads because that is the population I am most interested in. I used the csv file called: Most Recent Institution-Level Data that I found on their website.

This is important because it will help us predict what effects students' future earnings as well as gives an insight to how much schools matter and if there really is a signifcant difference in the careers between people who go to schools that cost more and people who do not. If not, then people should aim to save money in their education and not aim to go to expensive schools because after they have their degree, they will be making roughly the same amount of money, but if they went to an expensive school they will have more debt.

These are all of the libraries imported for the analysis

creates a dataframe from the csv file.

We import: INSTNM - institute name

CITY - city where college is located

STABBR - state abbreviation

PREDDEG - predominant undergraduate degree awarded

ICLEVEL - level of institution

ADM_RATE - admission rate

UGDS - The proportion of students or staff in specific race/ethnicity categories (including foreign students)

TUITIONFEE_IN - in state tuition fee

TUITIONFEE_OUT - out of state tuition

GRAD_DEBT_MDN - is a measure of the usual debt
accumualted by a student over the 4 year period

BBRR2_FED_UGCOMP_PAIDINFULL_SUPP - percent of student who paid their debt in full

MD_EARN_WNE_P10 - median earnings of students after they have graduated

ROOMBOARD_ON/OFF - cost of room/board for on/off campus

OTHER_EXPENSE_OFF/ON - other expenses for going to the school

Now that we have a dataframe with the features we want, I have to clean the data. I calculated the mean of offcampus expenses for cities or states depending on if there was enough city data and put them in for the missing values. For on campus, I replaced them with 0s because many of those schools did not offer dorms or other amenities that students would need to pay for.

I just dropped all universities with null values in the admission rate because replacing them with the mean or anything else might skew the data. Also any missing values in "GRAD_DEBT_MDN", I also dropped because calculating the mean might skew the data because even schools in the same state have different levels of debt. I did not drop based off of tuition values because those schools are military schools and are paid for by the military, so I just replaced them with 0s. I also filled in 0s for values that were missing in the "paid in full" column because those values are so low anyway that the mean would not be significantly greater than 0 and there were too many missing values for me to consider dropping rows.

Because of how important median earning for each school is to our conclusion, I dropped every row where that value is missing.

In [216]:
#find all undergrad data and store it in a dataframe
df_undergrad = df_features.loc[(df_features['ICLEVEL'] == 1) & (df_features['PREDDEG'] == 3)]

#replace "PrivacySuppressed with Nan"
df_undergrad.replace('PrivacySuppressed', np.nan)

#drop rows where any of these values are null
df_undergrad = df_undergrad.dropna(subset=['ADM_RATE'])
df_undergrad = df_undergrad.dropna(subset=['MD_EARN_WNE_P10'])
df_undergrad = df_undergrad.dropna(subset=['GRAD_DEBT_MDN'])

#stores all values where they are both null
df_offcampus_na =  df_undergrad[df_undergrad['ROOMBOARD_OFF'].isnull() & df_undergrad['OTHEREXPENSE_OFF'].isnull()]
#finds mean based off of city data
for row in df_offcampus_na['CITY']:
    roomboard = df_undergrad[df_undergrad['CITY'] == row]['ROOMBOARD_OFF'].mean()
    otherexpense = df_undergrad[df_undergrad['CITY'] == row]['OTHEREXPENSE_OFF'].mean()

    df_undergrad.loc[(df_undergrad['CITY'] == row) & (df_undergrad['ROOMBOARD_OFF'].isnull()) , 'ROOMBOARD_OFF'] = round(roomboard, 2)
    df_undergrad.loc[(df_undergrad['CITY'] == row) & (df_undergrad['OTHEREXPENSE_OFF'].isnull()) , 'OTHEREXPENSE_OFF'] = round(otherexpense, 2)
#if city data is not available, then bases it off state mean
for row in df_offcampus_na['STABBR']:
    roomboard = df_undergrad[df_undergrad['STABBR'] == row]['ROOMBOARD_OFF'].mean()
    otherexpense = df_undergrad[df_undergrad['STABBR'] == row]['OTHEREXPENSE_OFF'].mean()

    df_undergrad.loc[(df_undergrad['STABBR'] == row) & (df_undergrad['ROOMBOARD_OFF'].isnull()) , 'ROOMBOARD_OFF'] = round(roomboard, 2)
    df_undergrad.loc[(df_undergrad['STABBR'] == row) & (df_undergrad['OTHEREXPENSE_OFF'].isnull()) , 'OTHEREXPENSE_OFF'] = round(otherexpense, 2)


#fills in values with 0s
df_undergrad['ROOMBOARD_ON'] = df_undergrad['ROOMBOARD_ON'].fillna(0)
df_undergrad['OTHEREXPENSE_ON'] = df_undergrad['OTHEREXPENSE_ON'].fillna(0)
df_undergrad['BOOKSUPPLY'] = df_undergrad['BOOKSUPPLY'].fillna(0)
df_undergrad['TUITIONFEE_IN'] = df_undergrad['TUITIONFEE_IN'].fillna(0)
df_undergrad['TUITIONFEE_OUT'] = df_undergrad['TUITIONFEE_OUT'].fillna(0)
df_undergrad['BBRR2_FED_UGCOMP_PAIDINFULL_SUPP'] = df_undergrad['BBRR2_FED_UGCOMP_PAIDINFULL_SUPP'].fillna(0)

df_undergrad.isnull().sum()

Exploratory Analasysis and Data Visualization

The whole point of this section is to do a further analysis to get a better understanding of our data. This is for a better understanding of the relationships between our data which will later be used to make a model.

Fisrt, a scatterplot is made between student debt and student earnings to see the relationship between them. It appears as though most students earn between 40-60k and are in debt 20-25k. The GRAD_DEBT_MD is a measure of the usual debt accumualted by a student over the 4 year period. We measure that against the median earnings of students. Students included in this statistic are not currently enrolled in school.

Model: Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, Machine Learning

Machine learning involves the use of algorithms to develop models that can learn from data and make predictions or decisions without being explicitly programmed. These models aim to find patterns, relationships, and trends in data and generalize them to new, unseen data.

I made a regression line to get a better understanding between earning and debt, and the realtionship is weak because the majority of the data is nowhere near the line.

In [230]:
X = df_undergrad[['GRAD_DEBT_MDN']]
y = df_undergrad['MD_EARN_WNE_P10']
df_undergrad.isnull().sum()

#adds a constant term to the features (for the intercept)
X = sm.add_constant(X)

#creates and fit the OLS model
model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

#print the model summary
print(model.summary())

#creates a scatter plot with the OLS regression line
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x=X['GRAD_DEBT_MDN'], y=y, color='blue', label='Actual')
sns.lineplot(x=X['GRAD_DEBT_MDN'], y=model.predict(X), color='red', label='Predicted')
plt.xlabel('Average Student Debt')
plt.ylabel('Average of Students Earnings')
plt.title('OLS Regression: Average Student Debt vs Average of Students Who Paid Back Their Debt')
plt.legend()
plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()

Conclusion:

In conclusion, our analysis focused on the critical question of how various factors influence students' future earnings and whether the choice of an expensive education significantly impacts career outcomes. By leveraging hypothesis testing and machine learning techniques, we gained insights that are valuable for students and educators.

My investigation revealed important insights that could have far-reaching implications for prospective students and educational institutions. Specifically, we examined the influence of admission rates and the proportion of students who successfully repaid their debts on future earnings.

The results of our analysis demonstrate that both admission rates and the proportion of students who paid off their debts play significant roles in predicting future earnings. The admission rate of a school has a tangible effect on the career outcomes of its graduates. Furthermore, the proportion of students who managed to repay their debts reflects a level of financial responsibility and stability that is positively associated with future earnings.

This insight challenges the notion that expensive schools inherently guarantee higher future earnings. In fact, we found that the choice of an expensive education does not necessarily lead to substantially higher income levels after graduation. Rather, the admission rate and the financial behavior of students seem to be more influential factors.

These findings underscore the importance of making informed decisions when choosing educational paths. Prospective students should prioritize schools that offer a good balance between affordability, financial aid opportunities, and admission selectivity. Investing in an education that aligns with career goals and financial stability is paramount, as the allure of higher-cost institutions does not necessarily correlate with improved long-term earnings potential.

Ultimately, our analysis sheds light on the complex interplay between education, career outcomes, and financial responsibility. By recognizing the significant impact of admission rates and repayment behavior, individuals can make more informed choices that maximize the value of their education while minimizing the burden of student debt.

As the educational landscape continues to evolve, these insights provide a valuable guidepost for students, educators, and policymakers to shape decisions that lead to prosperous and financially sound futures.
